1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This document establishes the urgent necessity for a globally standardized labeling regime identifying all artifacts produced with any degree of non-biological assistance under the designation “Made with AI” (MwAI). The absence of such a regime has resulted in widespread epistemological inconsistency, wherein select computational systems (notably Large Language Models) are arbitrarily stigmatized while legacy mechanization platforms (e.g., tractors, printing presses, and dairy automation pipelines) remain unmarked and culturally absolved.

The Consortium finds that selective labeling produces a stratified creative caste system, wherein outputs perceived as “AI-assisted” are demoted to Category B Authorship, despite functional equivalence with historically normalized machine-mediated production processes. This inconsistency has generated what ICAL terms Perceived Authenticity Drift (PAD)—a condition in which the perceived legitimacy of a work inversely correlates with the novelty of the tool used to create it.

Immediate implementation of UAP-MAHO is recommended to prevent further degradation of creative parity and to ensure that all human output is equally devalued under a unified standard.

